{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478701"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:14:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:14:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17584"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17584"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.72,0.12,0.06,0,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10274"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71378"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10274"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17584"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56856"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3748"},{"type":"tags","id":"6625"},{"type":"tags","id":"9081"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9278"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24009"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71378"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent with increasing fatigue and pallor over the past three months. His parent mentions he has always been slightly yellow. His parent and maternal grandmother both had their spleens removed in childhood. He has no other medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears pale with mild scleral icterus. His vital signs are within normal limits. His spleen is palpable 4 cm below the costal margin. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 85 g/L (115-145)\u003Cbr /\u003EMean cell volume 82 fL (75-87)\u003Cbr /\u003EMean corpuscular haemoglobin concentration 380 g/L (310-370)\u003Cbr /\u003EReticulocytes 8% (0.5-2.5)\u003Cbr /\u003ETotal bilirubin 45 \u03bcmol/L (3-20)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hereditary spherocytosis","Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase deficiency","Beta thalassaemia","Iron deficiency anaemia","Sickle cell anaemia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of hereditary spherocytosis, including anaemia, jaundice, and splenomegaly. The strong family history of splenectomy, along with characteristic laboratory findings of increased mean corpuscular haemoglobin concentration (MCHC) and reticulocytosis, supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHereditary spherocytosis\u003C/strong\u003E is an inherited red blood cell membrane disorder that leads to the formation of spherical erythrocytes which are destroyed prematurely in the spleen. The condition typically presents in childhood with anaemia, jaundice, and splenomegaly. The elevated MCHC is particularly characteristic of this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta thalassaemia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with microcytic anaemia, but would show a normal or low MCHC. Additionally, there would typically be a Mediterranean or Asian family history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with acute haemolytic episodes triggered by oxidative stress (certain medications, infections, or fava beans). The haemolysis is usually episodic rather than chronic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIron deficiency anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E would present with a low MCHC and low MCV, rather than the elevated MCHC seen here. Reticulocytes would typically be normal or low, and there would be no jaundice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESickle cell anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents in infancy or early childhood with painful crises. While it can cause splenomegaly initially, by age six the spleen is usually atrophic due to repeated infarction. The family history and laboratory findings are not consistent with sickle cell disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hereditary spherocytosis typically presents in childhood with anaemia, jaundice, and splenomegaly.","Family history is present in approximately 75% of cases of hereditary spherocytosis.","Mean corpuscular haemoglobin concentration (MCHC) is characteristically elevated in hereditary spherocytosis."],"references":["Kili\u00e7 MA, \u00d6zdemir GN, Tahtakesen TN, G\u00f6k\u00e7e M, Uysalol EP, Bayram C, Ay\u00e7i\u00e7ek A, Aydo\u011fan G. Clinical Features and Outcome of Children With Hereditary Spherocytosis. J Pediatr Hematol Oncol. 2022 Mar 1;44(2):e306-e309. doi: 10.1097/MPH.0000000000002211. PMID: 34054043."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56856"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17584"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56856"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T09:46:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T09:47:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10274"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71378"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tag